Tom -

I don&#39;t know what the problem is.  Cantera usually installs fine on 
Windows PCs and everything runs.  Something about your system 
configuration must be non-standard, but I don&#39;t know what - some 
environment variable setting, for example.  Maybe try undefining both 
TMP and TEMP.  Or see if an older version of Cantera works on your 
system.  You could also try installing on someone else&#39;s PC to see if 
it is a problem specific to your machines.  Lots of people install 
Cantera using the Windows binary installer without problem, so I don&#39;t 
think it is anything fundamental in Cantera or in the install 
procedure...

Good luck,
Dave




